'''''Bad''''' is the seventh [[studio album]] by American recording artist [[Michael Jackson]]. The album was released on August 31, 1987<ref name="N.Y. Times, ''POP: MICHAEL JACKSON'S 'BAD,' FOLLOW-UP TO A BLOCKBUSTER''">[http://www.nytimes.com/1987/08/31/arts/pop-michael-jackson-s-bad-follow-up-to-a-blockbuster.html], New York Times, ''Pop: Michael Jackson's 'Bad,' Follow-Up to a Blockbuster"</ref> by [[Epic Records|Epic/CBS Records]], nearly five years after Jackson's previous studio album, ''[[Thriller (album)|Thriller]]'', which went on to become the [[List of best-selling albums worldwide|world's best-selling album]]. ''Bad'' itself has sold between 30 to 45 million copies worldwide, shipped 8 million units in the United States alone, and has been cited as [[List of best-selling albums worldwide|the fifth best selling album of all time]]. The album produced five Hot 100 number ones, the first album to do so. Similar to Jackson's previous music material, the album's music features elements of [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], pop and rock.

''Bad'' was recorded during the first half of 1987. The lyrical themes on the record relate to paranoia, romance and [[self-improvement]]. ''Bad'' is widely regarded as having cemented Jackson's status as one of the most successful artists of the 1980s, as well as enhancing his solo career and being one of the best musical projects of his career. Nine of the eleven songs on ''Bad'' were released as singles; one was a promotional single and another was released outside of the United States and Canada. Five of the singles hit number one in the United States, while a sixth charted within the top-ten, and a seventh charted within the top-twenty on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]. The single that was released outside of the United States and Canada was commercially successful, charting within the top ten and top twenty in multiple territories. ''Bad'' peaked at number one in seven countries, as well as charting within the top twenty in other territories. The only song on the album which wasn't released as a single nor had a music video for was "Just Good Friends".

''Bad'' saw Jackson exercise even more artistic freedom than he did with his two previous [[Epic Records|Epic]] releases (''[[Off the Wall (album)|Off the Wall]]'' and ''Thriller''). On ''Bad'', Jackson composed nine of the album's eleven tracks and received co-producer credit for the entire album. The album continued Jackson's commercial success in the late 1980s and garnered six [[Grammy Award]] nominations, winning two. Aside from commercial success the album also received critical acclaim from contemporary critics. ''Bad'' was ranked number 43 in the ''100 Greatest Albums of All Time of the MTV Generation'' in 2009 by [[VH1]] and number 202 in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's [[500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]. The album marked the final collaboration between Jackson and producer [[Quincy Jones]]. In addition, Jackson scored five number ones from ''Bad'', making him the first of only two artists in the chart's history to amass five number-one singles from one album. This feat would not be equaled for 23 years when [[Katy Perry]] did the same with her album ''[[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry album)|Teenage Dream]]''.

==Production==
Jackson's previous albums, ''[[Off the Wall (album)|Off the Wall]]'' and ''[[Thriller (album)|Thriller]]'', were critically and commercially successful,<ref name="allmusicreview"/><ref name="RS OTW">{{cite news|first=Stephen |last=Holden |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/259585/review/6067502/off_the_wall |title=Off the Wall: Michael Jackson |work=Rolling Stone |date=November 1, 1979 |accessdate=July 23, 2008|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071223010621/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/259585/review/6067502/off_the_wall |archivedate = December 23, 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref> eventually selling over 20&nbsp;million and 100&nbsp;million units worldwide, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1616537/20090720/jackson_michael.jhtml |title=Michael Jackson's Thriller Set To Become Top-Selling Album Of All Time |first=Kyle |last=Anderson |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom |date=2009-07-20 |accessdate=2010-02-18| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100210011128/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1616537/20090720/jackson_michael.jhtml| archivedate= February 10 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Jackson's aim for ''Bad'' was that it would sell 100&nbsp;million copies.<ref>{{cite book |url= http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BVC9zltjf-EC&pg=PA147#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Michael Jackson: the king of pop |page=147|author=Lisa D. Campbell |publisher=Branden Books|year= 1993 |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref>

''Bad'' was the second studio album Jackson released after leaving The Jackson 5, and the first in almost five years since ''Thriller''.<ref name="nytimesreview"/> ''Bad'' was the third, and final, musical collaboration between Jackson and [[Quincy Jones]]. The album was produced by Jones, with co-production credit given to Jackson.<ref name="linernotes"/> Jackson began recording demos for the anticipated follow-up to ''Thriller'' a few months after the 1984 [[Victory Tour (The Jacksons tour)|Victory Tour]] with [[The Jacksons]]. Development began in November 1986<ref name="otherinfo">{{cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1615214/20090702/jackson_michael.jhtml |title=Michael Jackson's Life & Legacy: The Eccentric King Of Pop (1986<U+2013>1999) |work=[[VH1]] |publisher=Viacom |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> and recording took place between January 5, 1987, and July 9, 1987,<ref name="linernotes">''Bad: Special Edition'' liner notes. [[Epic Records]] (2001).</ref> at [[Westlake Recording Studios|Westlake Audio]], where a special wooden stage was built to allow Jackson to dance while recording.<ref>{{cite book |url= http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BVC9zltjf-EC&pg=PA151|title=Michael Jackson: the king of pop |page=151|author=Lisa D. Campbell |publisher=Branden Books|year= 1993 |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref>
Jackson wrote a reported sixty songs for the new album and recorded thirty, wanting to use them all on a three-disc set.<ref name="otherinfo"/> Jones had suggested that the album be cut down to a ten-track single LP.<ref name="otherinfo"/> When the album was released on CD, a bonus 11th track, "[[Leave Me Alone (song)|Leave Me Alone]]" was included.<ref name="linernotes"/> It was later released as a single. Later reissues of the LP also include this song. Jackson was credited for writing nine out of eleven of the songs on the album.<ref name="otherinfo"/> Other writing credits included Terry Britten and Graham Lyle for "Just Good Friends" and [[Siedah Garrett]] and [[Glen Ballard]] for "Man in the Mirror".<ref name="linernotes"/>

==Composition==
{{Listen|filename=Michael Jackson - Bad.ogg|title=Bad (1987) |description=A 25-second sample of Jackson's "Bad" song where the chorus is played. The song's lyrics pertain to boasting, which was viewed by some music critics as Jackson referring to his stardom.}}
"[[Bad (Michael Jackson song)|Bad]]" was originally intended as a duet between Jackson and musician [[Prince (musician)|Prince]].<ref name="otherinfo"/> Other artists that were supposed to be featured on the album included [[Diana Ross]], [[Whitney Houston]], [[Aretha Franklin]] and [[Barbra Streisand]], but none of those collaborations ended up happening.<ref name="otherinfo"/> The album's song lyrics relate to romance and paranoia; paranoia was a recurring theme of Jackson's albums.<ref name="allmusicreview"/> [[Allmusic]] noted that ''Bad'' moved Jackson "deeper into hard rock, deeper into schmaltzy adult contemporary, deeper into hard dance <U+2013> essentially taking each portion of Thriller to an extreme, while increasing the quotient of immaculate studiocraft."<ref name="allmusicreview"/>

{{Listen|pos=left|filename=Michael Jackson - Dirty Diana.ogg|title=Dirty Diana|description=The lyrics to "Dirty Diana" pertain to a sexual predator, but unlike "Billie Jean", the sexual challenge is optional.<ref name=rollingstone/>|format=[[Ogg]]}}
"Dirty Diana" was viewed by critics as "misogynistic",<ref name="allmusicreview"/> and its lyrics, describing a sexual predator, do not aim for the "darkness" of "Billie Jean", instead sounding equally intrigued by and apprehensive of a sexual challenge, while having the opportunity to accept or resist it.<ref name=rollingstone/> "Leave Me Alone" was described as being a "paranoid anthem".<ref name="allmusicreview"/> "Man in the Mirror" was described as Jackson going "a step further" and offering "a straightforward [[homily]] of personal commitment", which can be seen in the lyrics, "I'm starting with the man in the mirror/I'm asking him to change his ways/And no message could have been any clearer/If you wanna make the world a better place/Take a look at yourself and then make a change."<ref name=rollingstone/> The lyrics to "Speed Demon" are about [[Speeding|driving fast]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/03/arts/critic-s-notebook-how-good-is-jackson-s-bad.html?n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fPeople%2fJ%2fJackson%2c%20Michael |title=Critic's Notebook; How Good Is Jackson's 'Bad'? |first=Jon |last=Pareles  |work=New York TImes |publisher=The New York Times Company |date=1987-09-03 |accessdate=2010-03-26}}</ref> "Bad" was viewed as a rived "Hit the Road, Jack" progression with lyrics that pertain to 'boasting'.<ref name=rollingstone/>

"Liberian Girl"'s lyrics were viewed as "glistening" with "gratitude" for the "existence of a loved one".<ref name=rollingstone/> "Smooth Criminal"'s recalled "the popcorn-chomping manner" of "Thriller".<ref name=rollingstone/> "Smooth Criminal" was thought of as an example of "Jackson's free-form language" that keeps people "aware that we are on the edge of several realities: the film, the dream it inspires, the waking world it illuminates".<ref name=rollingstone/> The music in "I Just Can't Stop Loving You", a duet with Siedah Garrett, consisted mainly of finger snaps and timpani.<ref name=rollingstone/> "Just Good Friends", a duet with Stevie Wonder, was viewed by critics as sounding good at the beginning of the song, ending with a "chin-bobbing cheerfulness".<ref name=rollingstone/> "The Way You Make Me Feel"'s music consisted of blues harmonies.<ref name="nytimesreview"/> The lyrics of "Another Part of Me" deal with being united, as "we".<ref name="nytimesreview"/>

==Release==
[[File:Michael Jackson The Way You Make Me Feel.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=A male with black hair singing into a microphone. The male is wearing a blue jacket and a white shirt with black pants and a white belt. |Jackson performing "The Way You Make Me Feel" during the [[Bad (tour)|Bad]] world tour]]

The album was released August 31, 1987.<ref>{{cite book |url= http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BVC9zltjf-EC&pg=PA153 |title=Michael Jackson: the king of pop |page=153|author=Lisa D. Campbell |publisher=Branden Books|year= 1993 |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref> By September 26, it had debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]],<ref name="billboarddbut">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/billboard-200?chartDate=1987-09-30 |title=September 26, 1987 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc]] |accessdate=2010-02-06| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100206054425/http://www.billboard.com/| archivedate= February 06 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> remaining there for the next six weeks.<ref name="1billboardsalesof2009">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/taylor-swift-edges-susan-boyle-for-2009-1004057203.story |title=Taylor Swift Edges Susan Boyle For 2009's Top-Selling Album |author=Keith Caulfield |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |date=2010-01-07 |accessdate=2010-02-06| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100206054425/http://www.billboard.com/| archivedate= February 06 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) certified ''Bad'' eight time platinum for having sold eight&nbsp;million copies in the United States alone.<ref name="RIAA certifications">{{cite web |url=http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?artist=%22Bad%22 |title=Gold and Platinum |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |accessdate=2008-04-27}}</ref> Though Jackson furthered his stance as a global pop superstar, in the United States ''Bad'' failed to match the sales of ''Thriller'', causing some in the media to label the album a "disappointment" in comparison.<ref name="otherinfo"/><ref name="mtvinfo09"/>

Internationally, ''Bad'' was commercially successful. In the United Kingdom, the album sold 500,000 copies in its first five days of release, and {{as of|2008|lc=yes}} is certified 13<U+00D7> platinum, for sales of 3.9 million, making it Jackson's second biggest-selling album in the United Kingdom.<ref name="bpi.co.uk">{{cite web |url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |title=Certified Awards Search |work=[[British Phonographic Industry|BPI.co.uk]] |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> ''Bad'' peaked at number one in 25 countries<ref name="Jet magazine">{{cite book |url=http://books.google.com.pe/books?id=3L0DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60&dq=best-selling+singles+of+the+80%27s&hl=en&sa=X&ei=rhJFT8qADYbD0QGz1umyBA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=best-selling%20singles%20of%20the%2080's&f=false |title=Michael Jackson Feted As Top Artist Of Decade After Selling 110 Million Discs|publisher=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet magazine]] |accessdate=2012-02-22}}</ref> including Canada,<ref name="canadacharts">{{cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0880&volume=46&issue=26&issue_dt=October%2003%201987&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=sp19smnjn4io5g2nmhli5tdfo5 |title=Top Albums/CDs <U+2013> Volume 46, No. 26, October 03 1987 |publisher=CollectionsCanada.gc.ca |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> Japan,<ref name="japancharts">{{cite web |url=http://ranking.oricon.co.jp/free_contents/search/ranking_list.asp?itemcd=13416&samecd=3&chart_kbn=11A&linkcd=30003278 |title=Bad |work=[[Oricon|Oricon.com]] |publisher=[[Oricon]] |accessdate=2010-02-08}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> the United Kingdom,<ref name="ukcharts">{{cite web |url=http://theofficialcharts.com/all_albums_album.php?id=493 |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> Bad |work=[[The Official Charts Company|TheOffcialCharts.com]] |publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=2010-02-08|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061112153452/http://theofficialcharts.com/all_albums_album.php?id=493 |archivedate = November 12, 2006|deadurl=yes}}</ref> Switzerland,<ref name="swisscharts1"/> New Zealand, Austria, Sweden and Norway.<ref name="leschartspositions"/> The album charted at number three in Italy and number thirteen in Spain, Mexico and Australia, as well as number twenty two in Puerto Rico.<ref name="leschartspositions">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Bad&cat=a |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> Bad (album) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-08| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100211235442/http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Bad&cat=a| archivedate= February 11 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> ''Bad'' has received various certifications worldwide. ''Bad'' was certified 7<U+00D7> platinum for the shipment of over 700,000 units in Canada by the [[Canadian Recording Industry Association]].<ref name="Canadian Recording Industry"/> In Europe, ''Bad'' was certified platinum by the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI) for the sales of one&nbsp;million units.<ref name="ifpi.fi">{{cite web |url=http://www.ifpi.fi/tilastot/artistit/michael+jackson |title=Michael Jackson: Albumi |work=IFPI.se |publisher=International Federation of the Phonographic Industry |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> The album was also certified platinum by the IFPI for the shipment of over 20,000 units in Hong Kong.<ref name="IFPI Hong Kong3"/> Globally, ''Bad'' is Jackson's overall second best-selling album, behind ''[[Thriller (album)|Thriller]]'', with a reported sales between 30 to 45 million units as of 2012.<ref name="Telegraph Bad 25">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/michael-jackson/8879265/Michael-Jackson-Bad-album-set-for-re-release.html|title=Michael Jackson Bad album set for re-release |accessdate=May 25, 2012 |publisher=Telegraphy|date=November 9, 2011}}</ref><ref name="NME Bad">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/photos/50-fastest-selling-albums-ever/213617/40/1|title=50 fastest selling albums ever |accessdate=May 25, 2012 |work=NME|year=2011}}</ref><ref name="MTV Bad">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1651633/michael-jacksons-new-album-cover-decoded.jhtml|title = Michael Jackson's New Album Cover Decoded Painting is packed with iconic MJ images
|accessdate=May 25, 2012 |work=mtv|year=2010|author=Gil Kaufman}}</ref><ref name="Reuters Bad 25">{{cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/05/21/entertainment-us-michaeljackson-bad-idUSBRE84K0Z120120521|title=Michael Jackson is still "Bad," 25 years after |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |publisher=Reuters|author=Piya Sinha-Roy|date=May 21, 2012}}</ref><ref name="Chicago Bad 25">{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-05-22/entertainment/sns-rt-us-michaeljackson-bad25bre84l17s-20120522_1_conrad-murray-dirty-diana-grammy-winning-album|title=Michael Jackson is still "Bad", 25 years after album |accessdate=May 22, 2012 |publisher=Chicagotribune|author=Piya Sinha-Roy|date=May 22, 2012}}</ref><ref name="Yahoo Bad 25">{{cite web|url=http://news.yahoo.com/25th-anniversary-michael-jackson-landmark-album-bad-celebrated-140242006.html|title=25th Anniversary Of Michael Jackson<U+2019>s Landmark Album Bad Celebrated With September 18 Release Of New Bad 25 Packages |accessdate=May 24, 2012 |publisher=Yahoo|year=2012}}</ref><ref name="contact Bad 25">{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/michael-jacksons-bad-to-get-25th-anniversary-release_1330641|title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> Michael Jackson's Bad To Get 25Th Anniversary Release |accessdate=May 25, 2012 |publisher=contactmusic|year=2012|author=contactmusic}}</ref>

===Marketing===
{{Main|Moonwalker|Bad (tour)}}

By the time ''Bad'' was released, ''Thriller'' had already sold millions, raising expectations for the new album. A commemorative special on Jackson's life, ''The Magic Returns'', was aired on [[CBS]] around the time of the release of ''Bad''.<ref name="nytimesreview"/> At the end of the documentary, the channel debuted [[Bad (Michael Jackson song)#Music video|the video]] of the title song from the album, "Bad", which was directed by Martin Scorsese and featured then up-and-coming actor [[Wesley Snipes]].<ref name="nytimesreview"/> The marketing strategy, mastered by Frank DiLeo among others, also included Jackson producing another mini-movie around the time of the [[Bad (tour)|Bad]] world tour. That film, ''[[Moonwalker]]'', included performances of songs from ''Bad'', including "[[Speed Demon (song)|Speed Demon]]", "[[Leave Me Alone]]", "[[Man in the Mirror]]" and "[[Smooth Criminal]]", the latter two released as sole videos at the end of the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117793231.html?categoryid=31&cs=1&p=0 |title=Moonwalker |author=Variety Staff |work=Variety |publisher=Reed Business Information |date=1988-01-01 |accessdate=2010-01-25}}</ref><ref name="latimesrevirem.w.">{{cite news |title=Video Review `Moonwalker': A Stroll Through a Super Ego |first=Dennis |last=Hunt |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=1989-01-10 |accessdate=2010-01-25}}</ref> Jackson's tour for ''Bad'' was a major financial success, grossing $125 million by the conclusion.<ref name="brooks 81">Brooks, p. 81</ref><ref name="grant 104 105">Grant, pp. 104<U+2013>105</ref>

===Singles===
The lead single "I Just Can't Stop Loving You" became the first of five of the album's singles to reach number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The song reached number one on September 19, 1987, and also charted on ''Billboard''{{'}}s [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|R&B/Hip Hop Songs]] chart and the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart, peaking at number one and number two respectively.<ref name="I.J.C.S.L.YCharts">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100#/charts/hot-100?chartDate=1987-09-19 |title=September 16, 1987 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=2010-02-06| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100206054835/http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100| archivedate= February 06 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}} {{dead link| date=June 2010 | bot=DASHBot}}</ref> Internationally, the song also peaked at number one, in three territories, United Kingdom, for two weeks,<ref name="uksingle1">{{cite web |url=http://theofficialcharts.com/all_singles_song.php?id=596 |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> I Just Can't Stop Loving You |publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=2010-02-06|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061112161740/http://theofficialcharts.com/all_singles_song.php?id=596 |archivedate = November 12, 2006|deadurl=yes}}</ref> and nine weeks in both Norway and New Zealand.<ref name="leschartssingle1">{{cite web |url=http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=I+Just+Can%27t+Stop+Loving+You&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> I Can't Stop Loving You (song) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-06| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100117052410/http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=I+Just+Can%27t+Stop+Loving+You&cat=s| archivedate= January 17 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The album's second single, "Bad", peaked at number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 on October 16, 1987.<ref name="BadCharts1">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100#/charts/hot-100?chartDate=1987-10-24 |title=October 24, 1987 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=2010-02-06| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100206054835/http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100| archivedate= February 06 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The song topped the Spanish charts, as well as charting within the top-ten internationally.<ref name="leschartssingle2">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Bad&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> Bad (chanson) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-06| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100211235742/http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Bad&cat=s| archivedate= February 11 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> "The Way You Make Me Feel" became the album's third consecutive single to peak at number one on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Hot 100.<ref name="T.W.Y.M.M.F.Charts">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100#/charts/hot-100?chartDate=1988-01-23 |title=January 23, 1988 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=2010-02-06| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100206054835/http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100| archivedate= February 06 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}} {{dead link| date=June 2010 | bot=DASHBot}}</ref> The song primarily charted within the top ten and twenty internationally.<ref name="leschartssingle3">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=The+Way+You+Make+Me+Feel&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> The Way You Make Me Feel (chanson) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-06| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100211233654/http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=The+Way+You+Make+Me+Feel&cat=s| archivedate= February 11 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> "Man in the Mirror" charted at number one on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Hot 100,<ref name="M.I.T.M.Charts">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100#/charts/hot-100?chartDate=1988-03-26 |title=March 26, 1988 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=2010-02-07| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100206054835/http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100| archivedate= February 06 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}} {{dead link| date=June 2010 | bot=DASHBot}}</ref> and charted at number four, eight, and ten in New Zealand, Australia, and Austria.<ref name="leschartssingle4">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Man+In+The+Mirror&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> Man in the Mirror (chanson) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-07| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100211235851/http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Man+In+The+Mirror&cat=s| archivedate= February 11 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> On July 2, 1988, "Dirty Diana" became the fifth consecutive, and final, single to peak at number one on the Hot 100.<ref name="DirtyDianaCharts">{{cite web |url= http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100#/charts/hot-100?chartDate=1988-07-02 |title=July 2, 1988 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=2010-02-07| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100206054835/http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100| archivedate= February 06 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> "Dirty Diana" was successful internationally, charting within the top ten in eight territories.<ref name="leschartssingle5">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Dirty+Diana&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> Dirty Diana (chanson) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-07| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100212001605/http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Dirty+Diana&cat=s| archivedate= February 12 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

"Another Part of Me" charted at number eleven on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, while topping the ''Billboard'' R&B/Hip Hop Songs chart.<ref name="A.P.O.M.Charts">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100#/song/michael-jackson/another-part-of-me/1539612 |title=Another Part Of Me <U+2013> Michael Jackson |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |accessdate=2010-02-07| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100206054835/http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100| archivedate= February 06 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}} {{dead link| date=June 2010 | bot=DASHBot}}</ref> Internationally, "Another Part Of Me" was a mid success compared to its previous singles, peaking at number five, fourteen and thirty two in the Netherlands, New Zealand and France.<ref name="leschartssingle6">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Another+Part+Of+Me&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> Another Part Of Me (chanson) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-07| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100211225258/http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Another+Part+Of+Me&cat=s| archivedate= February 11 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> "Smooth Criminal" became the sixth top ten single on the ''Billboard'' 100,<ref name="allmusiccharts">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r10093/charts-awards/billboard-single|pure_url=yes}} |title=allmusic ((( Bad <U+2013> Charts & Awards <U+2013> Billboard Singles ))) |work=Allmusic |publisher=Rovi Corporation |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref> and saw similar success internationally, charting within the top ten in five territories, and within the top forty in all its international countries.<ref name="leschartssingle7">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Smooth+Criminal&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> Smooth Criminal (chanson) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-07| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100211233555/http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Smooth+Criminal&cat=s| archivedate= February 11 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Released outside the United States and Canada, "Leave Me Alone" topped the Spanish charts, as well as peaking within the top ten in five other countries.<ref name="leschartssingle8">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Leave+Me+Alone&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> Leave Me Alone (chanson) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-07| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100211230517/http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Leave+Me+Alone&cat=s| archivedate= February 11 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The album's last official single was "Liberian Girl", which did not chart on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, but was generally successful internationally, charting mainly within the top twenty.<ref name="leschartssingle9">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Liberian+Girl&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> Liberian Girl (chanson) |work=LesCharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=2010-02-07| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100211234003/http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Liberian+Girl&cat=s| archivedate= February 11 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

==Critical reception==
{{Album ratings
| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]
| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name="allmusicreview"/>
| rev2 = [[Robert Christgau]]
| rev2Score = B+<ref name="rcgau"/>
| rev3 = ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]''
| rev3Score = favorable<ref name="nytimesreview"/>
| rev4 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''
| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name="rollingstone"/>
| rev5 = ''Rolling Stone''
| rev5Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>[http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/michael-jackson/albumguide]</ref>
| rev6 = [[Yahoo! Music]]
| rev6Score = favorable<ref name="yahoomusic"/>
}}
''Bad'' was generally well received although some critics noted that ''Bad'' did not measure up to ''Thriller'''s success. [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]], of [[Allmusic]], stated that Jackson "approached" ''Bad'' much the same way he approached ''Thriller'', which was to "take the basic formula of the predecessor, expand it slightly, and move it outward."<ref name="allmusicreview"/> Erlewine, who gave the album four and a half out of five stars, commented that while the album "rebounds with songs that prove mechanical can be tolerable if delivered with hooks and panache," it still made ''Bad'' feel like an artifact of its time instead a piece of music that transcends it."<ref name="allmusicreview">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/bad-r10093 |title=Michael Jackson <U+2013> Bad |author=Stephen Thomas |last=Erlewine |publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref> Davitt Sigerson, of ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'', stated that "even without a milestone recording like "[[Billie Jean]]", ''Bad'' is still a better record than ''Thriller''."<ref name=rollingstone>{{cite journal |title=Album Reviews: "Bad"|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/bad-19871022 |first=Davitt |last=Sigerson |work=Rolling Stone |publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media LLC]] |year=2001 |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref> Sigerson commented that "filler" songs in ''Bad'' such as "[[Speed Demon (song)|Speed Demon]]", "[[Dirty Diana]]" and "[[Liberian Girl]]" made ''Bad'' "richer, sexier and better than ''Thriller's'' forgettables."<ref name=rollingstone/>

Music critic [[Robert Christgau]] gave ''Bad'' a "B+" grade, remarking the "closest thing to genius" is the album's song "Leave Me Alone," and that the record "damn near wrecks perfectly good dancin' and singin' with subtext."<ref name="rcgau">{{cite web |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?id=932 |title=Michael Jackson: Consumer Guild Reviews |first=Robert |last=Christgau |publisher=RobertChristgau.com |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref> Jennifer Clay, of [[Yahoo Music]] noted that while ''Bad'' was good, it was not up to "the degree of ''Thriller''."<ref name="yahoomusic">{{cite web |url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/review/12040814 |title=Michael Jackson: Reviews |first=Jennifer |last=Clay |work=[[Yahoo! Music]] |publisher=Yahoo! Inc. |accessdate=2010-02-07}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Jon Pareles of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described ''Bad'' as being a "gleaming, high-tech dance record that's just a little eccentric at the edges".<ref name="nytimesreview"/> Parales also noted that ''Bad'' "sounds up-to-the-minute" and that the album also has a "concocted synthesizer-driven arrangements" that are "clear" and can "carry a solid kick."<ref name="nytimesreview">{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/1987/08/31/arts/pop-michael-jackson-s-bad-follow-up-to-a-blockbuster.html |title=Pop Review: Michael Jackson's 'Bad', A Follow Uo to a Blockbuster |first=John |last=Pareles  |work=The New York Times |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |date=1987-08-31 |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref> Richard Cromelin of ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' commented that the record was "not bad" and was more "reminiscent of ''Off the Wall''{{'}}s uniform strength than ''Thriller''{{'}}s peaks and valleys."<ref name="latimesreview"/> Cromelin felt that it would be "disappointing" if this album's "creative level" is where Jackson wants to stay.<ref name="latimesreview">{{cite news |title=Michael Jackson has a good thing in 'Bad' |first=Richard |last=Cromelin |work=The Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Company |date=1987-08-31 |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref>

Richard Harrington of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' commented on the expectations of ''Bad'' to ''Thriller'' that, "splashy though its prime-time introduction may be, the album begs to be judged by its music, not by its sales figures."<ref name="w.p.review"/> Richard felt that while the album could not live up to post-''Thriller'' expectations, it would be "considerably fairer to compare" ''Bad'' with ''Off the Wall''.<ref name="w.p.review"/> His overall opinion on ''Bad'' was that it was "a very good record" that is "immaculately produced and with some scintillating vocal performances from Jackson".<ref name="w.p.review">{{cite news |title=Jackson's `Bad': Looking Good; Not a `Thriller' but It's Full of Flash |first=Richard |last=Harrington |work=The Washington Post |publisher=The Washington Post Company |date=1987-08-31 |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref> Edna Gundersen of ''[[USA Today]]'' described ''Bad'' as  being Jackson's "most polished effort to date," that is "calculated but not sterile."<ref>{{cite news |title=The ever-changing Jackson, Michael jumps back and he's super `Bad' |first=Edna |last=Gundersen |work=USA Today |publisher=Gannett Co. Inc |date=1987-08-31 |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref> Thom Duffy of ''[[The Orlando Sentinel]]'' noted that some of the album's material "draws on even older musical roots".<ref>{{cite news |title=Jackson Re-emerges, Still Thrills With 'Bad' |first=Thom |last=Duffy |work=[[The Orlando Sentinel]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=1987-09-01 |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref> ''Bad'' was the recipient of six [[Grammy Award]] nominations, winning two. In 1988, ''Bad'' was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance|Best Pop Vocal Performance <U+2013> Male]], [[Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Performance|Best R&B Vocal Performance <U+2013> Male]]<ref name="Grammy 1988"/> and [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] for "Man in the Mirror" the following year.<ref name="Grammy 1989">{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1989/grammys.htm |title=Grammy Awards 1989 |publisher=Rock On The Net |accessdate=2010-02-18| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100204072231/http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1989/grammys.htm| archivedate= February 04 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> ''Bad'' won [[Grammy Award for Best Engineered Album, Non-Classical|Best Engineered Recording <U+2013> Non Classical]] in 1988,<ref name="Grammy 1988"/> and [[Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video|Best Music Video <U+2013> Short Form]] for "Leave Me Alone" in 1990.<ref name="Grammy 1990"/>

==Legacy==
[[File:Michael Jackson's "Bad" Jacket and Belt.jpg|thumb|upright|225px|alt=A black jacket with five round golden medals on its left and right shoulder and a gold ban on its left arm sleeve. The jacket has two belt straps on the right bottom sleeve. Underneath the jacket is a golden belt, with a round pendant in the center of it. There is a red light reflecting on the jacket and belt as well as a gold squared plat on the left side of the jacket and belt.|Jackson wore a gold-plated military styled jacket with a belt during the ''Bad'' era to give himself an edgier look.<ref name="otherinfo"/>]]
''Bad'' made history as being the first album to have five of its singles peak at number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 consecutively; "I Just Can't Stop Loving You", "Bad", "The Way You Make Me Feel", "Man in the Mirror" and "Dirty Diana" all charted at number one on the music chart.<ref name="otherinfo"/> Jayson Rodriguez of MTV, noted that "following the twin cannons that were ''Off the Wall'' and ''Thriller'' wouldn't be an easy task for most, but Jackson's follow-up, 1987's ''Bad'', was formidable by all accounts."<ref name="mtvinfo09"/> Rodriguez commented that the album was "wrongfully dismissed by critics because it wasn't the sales blockbuster that ''Thriller'' was" and that during the ''Bad'' era, Jackson's vocal hiccups and stammered "shamone" would become staples in his music that were "heightening and highlighting the emotion of his lyrics."<ref name="mtvinfo09">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1614758/20090625/jackson_michael.jhtml |title=Michael Jackson's Musical Legacy, From The Jackson 5 To Invincible |first=Jayson |last=Rodriguez |publisher=MTV |publisher=[[Viacom]] |date=2009-06-25 |accessdate=2010-02-08| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100109232039/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1614758/20090625/jackson_michael.jhtml| archivedate= January 09 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' commented that "the best way to view" ''Bad'' was not as "the sequel to ''Thriller''.<ref name=rollingstone/> In 2009, [[VH1]] said of the album,
{{quote|Understandably, the expectations for the album were ridiculously high, and grew even higher after Jackson planned duets with the likes of Prince (on the title track) and Whitney Houston (and Aretha Franklin and Barbra Streisand). None of those collaborations ended up happening, but they only increased the hype for the album. ''Bad'' was a deeply personal project for Jackson <U+2013> he wrote nine of the 11 songs <U+2013> one that saw him gain further independence and debut a harder-edged look and sound.<ref name="otherinfo"/>}}

Jim Farber of ''[[The New York Daily News]]'' felt that ''Bad'' "streamlined the quirks" of Jackson's two previous albums to "create his most smooth work of pop to date."<ref name="nydn2009">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/michael_jackson/2009/06/28/2009-06-28_for_michael_jackson_the_beat_went_on_after_thriller_hits_kept_coming.html#ixzz0ev5c4c9u |title=For Michael Jackson, the beat went on: after 'Thriller,' hits kept coming |first=Jim |last=Farber |work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]] |date=2009-06-29 |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> A writer for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' commented that while ''Bad''  was another worldwide commercial success, the album "inevitably failed to match the success of ''Thriller'' despite Jackson's massive and grueling world tour".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/celebrity-obituaries/5643156/Michael-Jackson.html |title=Michael Jackson |work=The Daily Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited |date=2009-06-26 |accessdate=2010-02-18}}</ref> In 2009, a writer for ''[[The Miami Herald]]'' reflected on the anticipation for ''Bad'', describing the album's release as being the "most hotly anticipated album in history".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12A99CBF149C2368&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=A Look Back |work=[[The Miami Herald]] |publisher=Miami Herald Media Co |date=2009-06-26 |accessdate=2010-02-18}}</ref> Stephen M. Silverman, a writer for [[People (magazine)|''People'' magazine]], viewed ''Bad'' as being "when some slippage" in Jackson's "popularity began to show".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20287810,00.html |title=Superstar: The Incredible Life of Michael Jackson 1958<U+2013>2009 |first=Stephen M. |last=Silverman |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |publisher=[[Time Warner|Time Warner Inc]] |date=2009-06-25 |accessdate=2010-02-18}}</ref>

In February 2012, it was announced by [[The Official UK Charts Company]] that ''Bad'' was the ninth best-selling album in British history with sales of 3.96 million units; ''Bad'' charted behind Jackson's ''Thriller''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/chart-news/adele-overtakes-michael-jackson-in-all-time-biggest-selling-albums-chart907/ |title=Adele overtakes Michael Jackson in all-time biggest selling albums chart |date=2012-02-28 |accessdate=2012-02-28}}</ref> ''Bad'', along with other studio albums released by Jackson, are among the best-selling albums of all-time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Music/06/26/michael.jackson.album.sales/ |title=Michael Jackson album sales soar |first=Mairi |last=Mackay |publisher=CNN |date=2009-06-26 |accessdate=2010-02-25| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100204040043/http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Music/06/26/michael.jackson.album.sales/| archivedate= February 04 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> In 2003, the album was ranked number 202 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's list of "[[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]".<ref name="Bad 202nd Best Album of All Time according to Rolling Stone Magazine"/> The album is included in the book entitled ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref name="1001 Series"/> In 2009, [[VH1]] listed the album at number 43 on their list of "100 Greatest Albums of All Time of the MTV Generation", in 2009.<ref name="Bad 43rd Best Album of All Time of the MTV Generation according to VH1"/> In 2012, [[Slant Magazine]] listed the album at No. 48 on its list of "Best Albums of the 1980s".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/feature/best-albums-of-the-1980s/308/page_6 |title=Best Albums of the 1980s &#124; Music |publisher=Slant Magazine |date= |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>

The album's songs have been covered and parodied by multiple recording artists since its release in the late 1980s. Notable cover versions include [[Alien Ant Farm]]'s cover of "Smooth Criminal" and [[Shakaya]]'s cover of "The Way You Make Me Feel". Notable parody versions include [["Weird Al" Yankovic]], who had previously recorded a parody of Jackson's song "Beat It".<ref name="parody1"/> Yankovic parodied "Bad", entitling his version "[[Fat (song)|Fat]]" in 1988; the song won a Grammy Award the same year for [[Grammy Award for Best Concept Music Video|Best Concept Music Video]].<ref name="parody1">{{cite web |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/29050662/michael_jackson_remembered_weird_al_yankovic_on_imitation_as_flattery |title=Michael Jackson Remembered: "Weird Al" Yankovic on Imitation as Flattery |work=Rolling Stone |publisher=Wenner Media LLC |date=2009-07-09 |accessdate=2010-02-07}} {{dead link| date=June 2010 | bot=DASHBot}}</ref>

